# bfx — Browser Forensic Explorer

Professional command-line tool for reading and analysing browser forensic
exports. Works on Windows, macOS, and Linux. Zero external dependencies —
pure Python 3.8+.

---

## Install

    cd bfx
    pip install -e .

After installing, the bfx command is available everywhere in your terminal.

---

## Workflow — two steps

### Step 1 — Export your browser databases

Point bfx at the browser folder and it extracts everything to CSV:

    bfx export --folder "C:\Users\cryfo\Desktop\Browser" --output .\exports

Other examples:

    # Chrome profile folder
    bfx export --folder "C:\Users\cryfo\AppData\Local\Google\Chrome\User Data\Default" --output .\exports

    # Single database file
    bfx export --file "C:\Users\cryfo\Desktop\Browser\History" --output .\exports

    # Preview — only first 500 rows per table
    bfx export --folder .\Browser --limit 500 --output .\preview

### Step 2 — Explore the export

All commands use --session to point at the folder created in Step 1.

---

## Commands and examples

### list — see all available tables

    bfx --session .\exports list

Example output:

    Session Tables  (53 loaded, 12 skipped)

    Browsing History & Downloads
      ├─ cluster-keywords           698 rows   5 cols
      ├─ downloads                  410 rows  28 cols  Download history
      ├─ keyword-search-terms       201 rows   4 cols  Search queries typed by user
      ├─ urls                      9142 rows  11 cols  All visited URLs
      └─ visits                    9778 rows   8 cols  Individual page visit events

    Saved Passwords (Hashed)
      └─ logins                      45 rows  10 cols  Saved login credentials

    Skipped (empty) tables written to: skipped_tables.txt

The name on the left of each line (e.g. urls, logins, downloads) is the
alias you use in all other commands.

---

### head / tail — quick look at first or last rows

    bfx --session .\exports head downloads --rows 20
    bfx --session .\exports tail visits --rows 10
    bfx --session .\exports head keyword-search-terms --rows 50
    bfx --session .\exports head urls --rows 5

---

### view — browse full table with pagination

    bfx --session .\exports view urls

Navigation: SPACE=next page, B=previous, Q=quit.

    # First 100 rows only
    bfx --session .\exports view urls --rows 100

    # Export table to CSV
    bfx --session .\exports view logins --export logins_review.csv

    # Output as JSON (pipeable)
    bfx --session .\exports view urls --json

---

### search — find a keyword across ALL tables at once

    bfx --session .\exports search "lazarus"

Shows every table that contains the word, with matching rows highlighted.

    # Narrow to one table
    bfx --session .\exports search "github" --table logins

    # Search within one column only
    bfx --session .\exports search "pdf" --col mime_type

    # Save all hits to a file
    bfx --session .\exports search "lazarus" --export lazarus_hits.csv

    # JSON output
    bfx --session .\exports search "gmail" --json

---

### filter — filter a table by column value

    # Only HTTPS URLs
    bfx --session .\exports filter urls --col url__CATEGORY --value HTTPS

    # Only dangerous downloads
    bfx --session .\exports filter downloads --col danger_type --value "^[^0]" --regex

    # Multiple conditions (AND logic)
    bfx --session .\exports filter downloads --col mime_type   --value zip \
                                             --col tab_url__CATEGORY --value HTTP

    # Save filtered result
    bfx --session .\exports filter urls --col url__CATEGORY --value HTTPS \
                                        --export https_only.csv

---

### schema — inspect column names and sample values

    bfx --session .\exports schema visits
    bfx --session .\exports schema logins --samples 10

Shows every column, whether it is original or enriched by bfx, and the
top N sample values in that column.

---

### info — forensic metadata for a table

    bfx --session .\exports info logins
    bfx --session .\exports info downloads

Shows: source database path, MD5 hash, export timestamp, column list.

---

### summary — session overview

    bfx --session .\exports summary

Shows: all tables with row counts, activity date range, top 10 visited
domains, top 10 search queries, download statistics.

---

## Enrichment columns explained

bfx automatically adds helper columns alongside timestamp and URL columns:

    Original column      Added columns                  Example value
    ─────────────────    ─────────────────────────────  ─────────────────────────────
    last_visit_time      last_visit_time__HUMAN         2023-10-11 18:18:44 UTC
                         last_visit_time__FORMAT        WebKit (Chrome)
    url                  url__DOMAIN                    google.com
                         url__CATEGORY                  HTTPS

In card view these appear indented under the raw value:

    tab_url      https://malware-site.ru/payload.zip
                     -> malware-site.ru | HTTP
    start_time   13341800000000000
                     -> 2023-10-14 09:00:00 UTC | (WebKit (Chrome))

---

## Disable colour

    bfx --no-color --session .\exports list

Or permanently:

    set NO_COLOR=1          (Windows CMD)
    $env:NO_COLOR=1         (PowerShell)
    export NO_COLOR=1       (Linux / Mac)

---

